05757nam a22006975i 9781800734982DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818007349827 a10.1515/97818007349822doi  a(DE-B1597)658642  a(OCoLC)1222778777  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aMED0580602bisacsh04a616.8/31qOCoLC223/eng/2023112000aPreventing Dementia? :bCritical Perspectives on a New Paradigm of Preparing for Old Age /ced. by Annette Leibing, Silke Schicktanz. 1aNew York ;aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife Course, Culture and Aging: Global Transformations ;v700tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Figures -- tIntroduction. Reflections on the "New Dementia" -- tPART I. The Discursive and Social Practices of Dementia Prevention -- t1. A Window to Act? Revisiting the Conceptual Foundations of Alzheimer's Disease in Dementia Prevention -- t2. The Vascularization of Alzheimer's Disease: Prevention in "Glocal" Geriatric Care -- t3. If Dementia Prevention Is the Answer, What Was the Question? Observations from the German Alzheimer's Disease Debate -- t4. Dementia Prevention: Another Expansion of the Preventive Horizon -- t5. Mind's Frailty: Elements of a "Geriatric Logic" in the Clinical Discourse about Dementia Prevention -- tPART II. From the Prediction and Early Detection to the Prevention of Dementia -- t6. Revisiting MCI: On Classificatory Drift -- t7. The Preventive Uncertainty of Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI): The Experts, the Market, and the Subjects of Diagnosis -- tPART III. Conceptual Premises and Normative Claims of Prevention -- t8. Staging Prevention, Arresting Progress: Chronic Disease Prevention and the Lifestyle Frame -- t9. Responsibilization of Aging? An Ethical Analysis of the Moral Economy of Prevention -- t10. Governing through Prevention: Lifestyle and the Health Field Concept -- tAfterword. Looking Forward -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe conceptualization of dementia has changed dramatically in recent years with the claim that, through early detection and by controlling several risk factors, a prevention of dementia is possible. Although encouraging and providing hope against this feared condition, this claim is open to scrutiny. This volume looks at how this new conceptualization ignores many of the factors which influence a dementia sufferers' prognosis, including their history with education, food and exercise as well as their living in different epistemic cultures. The central aim is to question the concept of prevention and analyze its impact on aging people and aging societies.  afunded by SSHRC (Social Sciences and Humanities Council of Canada)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aMEDICAL / Nursing / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBallantyne, Peri J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlasimme, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoth, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Daniel R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeuck, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeanza, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeibing, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/